Yes! If you're working with owned data (like Vec<i32>) and want to avoid unnecessary clones, Cow<T> is perfect. Here's a quick example:

```rust
use std::borrow::Cow;

fn modify_data(data: &mut i32) {
    *data += 10;
}

generic function with Cow

fn process_with_cow(input: Cow<i32>) -> Cow<i32> {
    let mut modified = input.into_owned();
    modify_data(&mut modified);
    Cow::Owned(modified)
}
```

Here, if the original is owned, you get an owned back; otherwise (if borrowed), you get a copy. This avoids unnecessary cloning, which can be memory expensive for larger data structures.

So use Cow<T> when you want to work with mutable or immutable references flexibly, but avoid it for types where clone() doesn't incur significant overhead.
